recordings.rmk:
Singing from a hedgerow ash tree. The track opens with a Blackbird followed immediately by the Blackcap mimicking this species. There are further occasions when the Blackcap mimicks Blackbirds such as 1:43.5, 4:33.0, 4:43.2 and 6:26.0. At 6:48.5 either a Blackbird or Mistle Thrush sounds like it is imitated. There are probably further examples of mimicry in there, a number of repeated phrases are certainly reminiscent of Song Thrush song and a few sections remind me of Siskins (5:02.1, 5:37.8 and 6:15.2).

 Most of the verses starts with a variety of phrases and finish with the typical fluty Blackcap notes. Towards the end the bird sings more subdued phrases before flying off. 
Recorded with an Olympus LS-12 and Sennheiser ME66 handheld. 
EQ lightly adjusted below 1400 Hz to remove some handling noise and distant vehicles.

You may find the time references do not accurately point to the actual referred times, as discussed in [Forum topic 25398](https://www.xeno-canto.org/forum/topic/25398).

recordings.rmk:
Blackcap song from about 50 minutes after the bird first started singing. Among its repertoire - and not uncommonly from among the repertoire of other Blackcaps that I have listened to - there is the occasional  phrase that to my ears sounds a bit like a Nightingale.  I know Nightingale song from several trips in spring to Catalonia.  The phrase in question can be heard just after 0:10. A Buzzard calls at 1:03 (four calls over the next five seconds).

Blackcaps indulge in mimickry. One singer that, unfortunately, I failed to record, began his song with several perfect Blackbird phrases. So much so that I was astonished when he broke into typical voice - it was a Blackcap.  In this recording, it strikes me that the opening three seconds could well be a sample of Robin. If you heard say, just the first three seconds, would you not think you were listening to a Robin?

recordings.rmk:
This is the same male that featured in XC552441. Unlike the latter recording, there is no rival singing in competition. This individual Blackcap has a trademark 'yodel' that it uses in almost all its verses. The yodel (for want of a better word) is included in this clip - but it was noticeably absent when the bird was involved in direct competition with a rival. The yodel - a kind of alternating change in scale, a bit like a boogie-woogie riff on a piano, can be heard at 0:07; 0:18; 0:30; 0:42. Unlike in XC552441, the Blackcap had largely ceased its mimicry of Blackbird. Nonetheless, you can again here Blackbird samples at 0:15 and 0:26. For some reason, the Blackbird samples from this passage of singing are much more embedded in the overall composition - and could easily be overlooked. 

From this and other Blackcaps I sometimes hear a fleeting haunting sound that reminds me of Nightingale. I do not know if the birds are actually copying Nightingales - that they presumably hear when the two species overlap on migration in Spain and maybe southern France - or create the sound themselves. The sound I mean is at 0:38 and lasts roughly two seconds. 

Other species in the clip are: Wren (0:10) and Great Tit (0:13; 0:20; 0:26).

recordings.loc: Ireland (near  Bangor), Ards and North Down, Northern Ireland
recordings.rmk:
This recording is an extract from several hours of vocal arm-wrestling between two rival male Blackcaps. Competition seems to be at maximum intensity, heightened further because at least one female Blackcap was in the area. Maybe she was partnered to one of the males? Both males had been in the area for over a fortnight. Initially - and presumably before any female arrived - the song was less prolonged and lacked much mimicry of other species.  Competition seems to have spurred the males to 'raise their game'. Hence the song bursts are longer and more sustained, with bits of mimicry included as some kind of added embellishment. Six verses are on the clip. The duration of most exceeds the five or six seconds that is typical of song bursts when the birds first arrive in early April (such as XC552444).  Two bursts are over ten seconds; one lasts 26 seconds (from 1:03).  Mimicry of Blackbird can be heard at 0:34-36 (start of third verse); 0:42-44 (start of fourth verse); 0:52-54 (end of fourth verse). In these - and other instances, not on the clip - mimicry is either at the beginning or end of a song burst.  The verbal battle has the briefest of breaks. I assume the breaks are only because one male is pausing to check if its rival is still singing. Unlike other songbirds that indulge in singing contests, Blackcaps sing against each other and overlap their efforts. They do not take it in turns - as Robins, Dunnocks, Blackbirds and others do. The same Blackcap can be heard at XC552452 - but singing on his own, when he seems less animated. The rival either went quiet or moved elsewhere. 

A Woodpigeon utters its classic broadcast sequence at 0:15 until the 24th second.

Madeira's Blackcaps belong to the subspecies Sylvia atricapilla heineken. On 'passable' views, I could not see any plumage differences between Madeira Blackcaps and those that I see regularly in Ireland. The overall 'feel' of the song was also the same but, in some areas, some Madeira Blackcaps had a habit of repeating a note - either two notes in succession, sometimes three, rarely four. I do not remember hearing this habit in singing Blackcaps elsewhere. On this clip you can hear the repetition at 0:03, 0:08, 0:17, 0:30 and 0:44 - at this last part of a song burst, you can hear one note repeated four times.

Another recording of a different Madeira Blackcap that also repeats is XC491882. Another recording of a Madeira Blackcap without any repetition is XC491799.

Madeira's Blackcaps belong to the subspecies Sylvia atricapilla heineken. On 'passable' views, I could not see any plumage differences between Madeira Blackcaps and those that I see regularly in Ireland. The overall 'feel' of the song was also the same but, in some areas, some Madeira Blackcaps had a habit of repeating a note - either two notes in succession, sometimes three, rarely four.  I do not remember hearing this habit in singing Blackcaps elsewhere. On this clip you can hear the repetition at 0:03, 0:29 at 0:33. Normally (based on this singer and several others that also repeated notes) the repetition is near the end of the song burst, but at 0:45 the repeated notes are near the beginning.

Another recording of a different Madeira Blackcap that also repeats is XC491883. Another recording of a Madeira Blackcap without any repetition is XC491799. And, in order to compare a non-repeating Madeiran Blackcap with a west European singer - from Northern Ireland - you can listen here to XC491797. In my view, the two songs, while not identical, are typical. I could not tell them apart, in terms of being made by a Blackcap.  

Background species: Collared Dove, Plain Swift, Madeiran Kinglet (local subspecies of Firecrest)

This Blackcap was recorded singing on Madeira, making it referable to the subspecies S.a. heineken. Based on looking at several Blackcaps on Madeira (although the views were not close or prolonged) I felt that they looked just the same as Blackcaps I see in Ireland. The voice of this singing male seems, to my ears, to be no different to what I regard as typical Blackcap song - as heard in Ireland.

Other Blackcaps on Madeira used some repetition in their songs. I have not heard Blackcaps use repetition in Ireland (or elsewhere in Britain). I have added two clips from Madeira - a different Blackcap in each clip - that feature repeated notes in songs: XC491882 and XC491883.

An interesting special singer. First in a long fore- or chattering song (4 min) he imitates a lot  (including Common Blackbird, C. Chiffchaff, Nightingale), while moving through low bushes. In the following rich main song with art typical loops (Überschlägen) he sits in a higher tree also imitating and repeats very often an individual beautiful flute motive. 
Habitat: forest edge

The bird was singing at the treeline, in the middle of a bush, in a grassy meadow, on a south-facing slope. After asking for help from Bram Piot, posting it as a mystery bird and getting a helpful comment from Piotr Szczypinski, I came to the conclusion that it must be another unusual Eurasian Blackcap song. Thanks to Bram Piot and Piotr Szczypinski for their help.
